The paper deals with the problem of ranking competitors in a generalized tournament, which involves measuring the outcome of games cardinally with a lower and upper bound. This problem is relevant to several areas of computer science, including game theory (cs.GT), data structures (cs.DS), artificial intelligence (cs.AI), machine learning (cs.LG), and social and information networks (cs.SI). The axiomatic approach used in the paper is also commonly employed in these subfields. Therefore, it is likely that the paper could be classified under any of these sub-categories, with cs.GT being the most likely due to its direct relevance to the problem of ranking in games.
